# benchmark-gpu-inference

This skill turns one prompt into a measured benchmark report.

## When to invoke

Trigger phrases (not exhaustive):

- "benchmark inference on this GPU"
- "compare vLLM vs SGLang vs TRT-LLM for <model>"
- "run the NitroGen optimization sweep"
- "which backend is fastest for <model> on <GPU>"
- "how many concurrent sim agents per GPU"

If the user only wants raw scenario building, use [prepare-nitrogen-dataset](../prepare-nitrogen-dataset/SKILL.md).
If they only want to install a backend, use [setup-inference-backend](../setup-inference-backend/SKILL.md).
If they only want to read existing results, use [interpret-benchmark-summary](../interpret-benchmark-summary/SKILL.md).

## The five-step flow

Every benchmark run goes through the same five `bench` commands. JSON
mode is on each so you can branch on `status` without parsing logs.

```bash
# 1. Identify the GPU + the per-venv backend versions installed.
bench probe --json

# 2. Make sure the backend(s) you need have a venv. Idempotent — skips
#    if already present.
bench setup --backend nitrogen --json
bench setup --backend vllm --json       # add more if the sweep needs them

# 3. Build scenarios for the workload. NitroGen for policy benchmarks;
#    tests/smoke/scenarios/ for VLM benchmarks.
bench scenarios build --source nitrogen --n 3 \
  --actions-root /path/to/extracted/SHARDS \
  --synthetic-frames \
  --json

# 4. Smoke one round to confirm a (backend, model) combo works on this
#    GPU before paying for a full sweep.
bench smoke --gpu rtx_pro6000 --backend nitrogen-eager \
  --model nitrogen-500m-bf16 \
  --scenarios-dir tests/smoke/scenarios_nitrogen \
  --json

# 5. Run the sweep + read the summary.
bench sweep --gpu rtx_pro6000 --sweep nitrogen-backends \
  --backends "nitrogen-eager nitrogen-compile nitrogen-cudagraph" \
  --scenarios-dir tests/smoke/scenarios_nitrogen \
  --json
bench summary --gpu rtx_pro6000 --json
```

Pick the GPU profile from the names under [benchmarks/configs/](../../benchmarks/configs/):
`rtx_pro6000`, `h200`, `rtx5090`. Pick a `--sweep` name from the
`sweeps:` block of the same yaml; without `--sweep`, the runner does a
single-round run on the default model.

## Failure recovery (don't ask the user)

| `error.code` from JSON | Meaning | What to do |
|---|---|---|
| `2` | combo unsupported per yaml `unsupported_backends` | Drop the offending backend from `--backends`, rerun. Note the reason in the final report. |
| `3` | runtime crash (OOM, server failed, kernel incompat) | Check `benchmarks/results/<gpu>/server-logs/<backend>.log`. If "Address already in use", another engine is holding the port — kill it, rerun (PR #1 spread nitrogen ports to 5560-5564 per engine to prevent this). |
| `4` | missing dep / credential | If `bench setup` failed: try the `next_action` hint in its JSON (often "now install: …"). If HF model gated: `huggingface-cli login`. |
| `1` | generic | Print the `error.remediation` text and stop. |

## Reading the result

After step 5, `bench summary` writes `benchmarks/results/<gpu>/summary.md`.
**Do NOT paraphrase it freehand.** Hand off to
[interpret-benchmark-summary](../interpret-benchmark-summary/SKILL.md),
which applies the validated Core-findings style (winner first, why +
how-to-improve for under-performers).

